mbranes","Visceral pleura lines the chest wall","Parietal pleura covers the lung surface","Parietal and visceral pleura are directly connected"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Evisceral pleura covers the lung surface and extends into the fissures\u003C/strong\u003E between lobes. This arrangement allows for smooth movement of the lung lobes against each other during breathing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPleural space contains air between the membranes\u003C/strong\u003E - The pleural space normally contains only a small amount of serous fluid, not air. The presence of air (pneumothorax) is pathological\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVisceral pleura lines the chest wall\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect as the visceral pleura covers the lung surface while the parietal pleura lines the chest wall\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParietal pleura covers the lung surface\u003C/strong\u003E - The parietal pleura lines the inner surface of the thoracic cavity, including the costal surface, mediastinum, and diaphragm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParietal and visceral pleura are directly connected\u003C/strong\u003E - The pleural membranes are separated by the pleural space containing a small amount of lubricating fluid\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pleural membranes and the fluid-filled pleural space between them are crucial for maintaining normal lung mechanics and allowing efficient breathing movements.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The visceral pleura covers the surface of the lungs and extends into the fissures between lobes.","The parietal pleura lines the inner surface of the thoracic cavity and is divided into costal, mediastinal, and diaphragmatic parts.","The 